VALUES
(40, 16, 1, 44, 4, 1, 1, 'Sadducees', 'Pharisees and Sadducees Encounter', 'Both passages emphasize the involvement of the Sadducees in challenging the authority of religious figures. In Matthew, they seek a sign from Jesus, while in Acts, they confront the apostles, indicating a continued opposition to divine authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 1, 41, 8, 11, 21, 'a sign from heaven', 'Demand for Signs from Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the request for a sign from heaven by the Pharisees. This connection highlights the skepticism of the religious leaders and Jesus'' response to their demand, indicating a theme of misunderstanding and lack of faith.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 1, 43, 8, 6, 6, 'tempting', 'Temptation of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of tempting Jesus. In Matthew, the Pharisees and Sadducees seek a sign, while in John, others attempt to accuse him. This connection highlights the recurring theme of challenges posed to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 1, 46, 1, 22, 22, NULL, 'Demand for Signs in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the demand for signs, highlighting the Jewish expectation for miraculous proof. In Matthew, the Pharisees and Sadducees seek a sign from heaven, while in Corinthians, it is stated that the Jews require a sign.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 1, 42, 11, 29, 30, 'sign from heaven', 'Demand for Signs in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the request for a sign, highlighting the skepticism of the Pharisees and the people. Jesus responds by indicating that only a specific sign will be given, linking their demand to a prophetic example.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 2, 42, 12, 54, 56, 'ye say, It will be fair weather', 'Weather Signs and Discernment', 'Both passages emphasize the ability to interpret weather signs, highlighting the contrast between physical discernment and spiritual insight. They illustrate the hypocrisy of recognizing natural phenomena while failing to understand the significance of the present time.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 3, 42, 12, 56, 56, 'ye hypocrites', 'Hypocrisy in Weather Discernment', 'Both passages emphasize the ability to discern signs in nature while criticizing the failure to recognize spiritual signs. The repeated use of ''ye hypocrites'' highlights the inconsistency in their understanding.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 3, 13, 12, 32, 32, 'discern the signs of the times', 'Understanding the Times', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of discerning the signs of the times. Matthew critiques those who can read the weather but not the spiritual climate, while 1 Chronicles highlights the men of Issachar who understood the times to guide Israel''s actions.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 3, 40, 11, 5, 5, 'can ye not discern the signs of the times?', 'Signs of Healing and Awareness', 'This connection highlights the ability to discern significant events. Both passages emphasize recognizing the signs of divine action, with Matthew 16:3 questioning the ability to perceive spiritual truths, while Matthew 11:5 lists miraculous signs that demonstrate God''s work.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 3, 42, 13, 15, 15, 'ye hypocrites', 'Hypocrisy and Discernment Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy in both passages. In Matthew, Jesus criticizes the ability to discern weather signs while failing to recognize spiritual truths, while in Luke, He points out the hypocrisy of prioritizing animal care over the Sabbath laws.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 3, 40, 4, 23, 23, 'discern the signs of the times', 'Signs of the Times and Healing', 'This connection highlights the theme of discernment in both passages. In Matthew 16:3, the ability to discern signs is contrasted with the healing ministry of Jesus in Matthew 4:23, suggesting a deeper understanding of the kingdom''s presence through miraculous acts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 4, 42, 11, 29, 30, 'the sign of the prophet Jonas', 'Connection of Sign of Jonas', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''sign of Jonas'' and describe the generation seeking a sign. They highlight the significance of Jonas as a sign for the people, linking the prophetic message to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 4, 40, 12, 39, 40, 'the sign of the prophet Jonas', 'Connection of Sign of Jonas', 'Both passages emphasize that a wicked generation seeks a sign, specifically mentioning the sign of the prophet Jonas. This connection highlights the parallel in Jesus'' response to the demand for signs, reinforcing the significance of Jonas'' experience as a foreshadowing of His own.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 4, 32, 1, 17, 17, 'the sign of the prophet Jonas', 'Sign of Jonah Connection', 'This connection highlights the significance of Jonah''s three days and nights in the fish as a foreshadowing of Jesus'' own death and resurrection. Both passages emphasize the theme of a sign given to a generation seeking proof.', 'typology', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 4, 41, 8, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Generational Signs', 'Both passages emphasize the generation seeking after a sign. They also state that no sign shall be given to this generation, highlighting a shared theme of disbelief.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 4, 41, 8, 38, 38, 'adulterous generation', 'Adulterous Generation Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''adulterous generation,'' highlighting a shared theme of moral failure. This connection underscores the rejection of Jesus and the consequences for those who are ashamed of Him.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 4, 40, 15, 14, 14, NULL, 'Blindness and Seeking Signs', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness in both passages. In Matthew 16:4, the ''wicked and adulterous generation'' seeks signs, while in Matthew 15:14, the ''blind leaders'' lead others into error, suggesting a lack of true understanding.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 4, 1, 6, 3, 3, 'wicked and adulterous generation', 'Divine Response to Human Behavior', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s response to human wickedness. In both passages, there is a sense of divine judgment against a generation characterized by sin and rebellion.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 5, 41, 8, 13, 14, 'had forgotten to take bread', 'Disciples'' Forgetfulness of Bread', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' forgetfulness regarding bread, highlighting a shared moment of concern during their journey. This connection illustrates a recurring theme of the disciples'' misunderstanding of their situation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 5, 40, 15, 39, 39, NULL, 'Connection of Bread and Travel', 'This connection highlights the theme of travel and provision. In Matthew 16:5, the disciples'' forgetfulness about bread occurs after they have traveled, paralleling the journey mentioned in Matthew 15:39.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 6, 42, 12, 1, 1, 'leaven of the Pharisees', 'Connection of Leaven and Hypocrisy', 'Both passages emphasize the ''leaven of the Pharisees,'' warning against their influence. This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy as a corrupting force within religious leadership.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 6, 40, 16, 12, 12, 'leaven of the Pharisees and of the Sadducees', 'Leaven of the Pharisees', 'This connection highlights the metaphorical use of ''leaven'' in both passages, where Jesus warns against the ''leaven of the Pharisees and of the Sadducees.'' The second passage clarifies that this leaven refers to their ''doctrine,'' emphasizing the importance of discerning false teachings.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 6, 48, 5, 9, 9, 'leaven of the Pharisees and of the Sadducees', 'Leaven''s Influence in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the concept of leaven as a metaphor for influence. Both passages emphasize how a small amount of leaven can affect a larger whole.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 6, 3, 2, 11, 11, 'leaven of the Pharisees and of the Sadducees', 'Leaven as a Symbol', 'This connection highlights the negative connotation of leaven in both passages. In Matthew, leaven represents the corrupting influence of the Pharisees and Sadducees, while in Leviticus, leaven is prohibited in offerings, symbolizing purity and holiness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 6, 46, 5, 6, 8, 'leaven of the Pharisees and of the Sadducees', 'Leaven as a Symbol of Influence', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of leaven as a corrupting influence. In Matthew, Jesus warns against the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees, while in Corinthians, Paul uses leaven to illustrate the need for purity and sincerity in the community.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 6, 41, 8, 15, 15, 'leaven of the Pharisees', 'Leaven of the Pharisees Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the warning against the leaven of the Pharisees, indicating a shared concern about corrupting influences. The mention of leaven in both contexts suggests a thematic link regarding spiritual caution.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 6, 55, 2, 16, 17, 'leaven of the Pharisees and of the Sadducees', 'Warning Against Corrupting Influence', 'This connection highlights the theme of caution against corrupting influences. Both passages emphasize the danger of teachings that lead to ungodliness, with ''leaven'' symbolizing pervasive negative influence in Matthew and ''canker'' representing destructive words in 2 Timothy.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 7, 41, 8, 16, 18, NULL, 'Disciples'' Misunderstanding of Bread', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' reasoning about bread, indicating their lack of understanding. Jesus questions their perception and memory regarding previous miracles involving bread.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 7, 40, 15, 16, 18, NULL, 'Understanding and Defilement', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of understanding spiritual truths over physical concerns. The disciples'' reasoning about bread in Matthew 16:7 contrasts with Jesus'' teaching in Matthew 15:16-18 about what truly defiles a person.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 16, 7, 41, 9, 10, 10, NULL, 'Disciples'' Confusion and Questioning', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' tendency to reason among themselves in response to Jesus'' teachings. Both passages emphasize their confusion and questioning about significant spiritual matters.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
